Germany, Year Zero
May 8th always reminds me of the year 1945. For the end of the war in Europe was indeed a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resister, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide as I did after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
After the Nazis left, the occupying powers had not yet established an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have a few romantic poetry volumes I recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to get food.
My father was taken directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and was tasked - from nothing - with setting up the city's energy supply office.
For a certain time, there was neither electricity, nor transportation, nor organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate issue, even though for our family it was clearly a liberation in every sense of the word.
But what for?
For what future?
"you must help me," my mother said to me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card of "victim of fascism," while others wore a Iron Cross awarded for services rendered late to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, and almost all mourned the disappearance of loved ones.
However, this stage did not last.
It's almost unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and above all accompanied by a new form of servitude.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the contrary, after a brief period of non-cooperation, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled strengthening of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not a mere word, and it was based on German traditions.
Certainly, not everything was goodwill on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and everyone wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic nature and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy undoubtedly takes root more easily in a context of economic recovery.
For this, one must above all have initiative from individuals who wish to end a period of suffering.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with a starting capital.
Hence the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
In the same way, the European Union has helped the former communist countries and continues to support them in their efforts.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of the Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long journey by worrying about the past.
In fact, many have described the years after 1949 under Adenauer as a period of “restoration,” since too many minor Nazi figures remained in their positions.
In a certain way, the country ignored its past in order to move forward into the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced its past with great success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other devastated countries are therefore misleading.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to come to terms with the past.
In the end, it's a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an opportunity to look back with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the past decades and therefore filled with hope.
